		Comment <a href="#c_1713653855">7</a> by mike
		posted on 6/3/2006 at 10:18 PM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>Ray.. it actually could be bad gas.. gas does go bad if it sits in a tank for a long period of time, especially if there is some water and heat in the mix.  I've run up against this with motorcycles that aren't ridden much.  It also causes all kinds of problems because the gas will cause something like a shellac buildup on parts as it sits and ages.  I've bought several old motorcycles that ran like crap until I took the carburators apart and cleaned out the buildup left behind by the gas.</p><p>But.. your car is only a year old, and you run through a tank of gas every month or so, right?  So odds are that's not the problem.  The gas you bought could have been bad (water in it perhaps?) but not likely.</p><p>So, It may not be a gas or mechanical issue with the car that can be fixed... one of your reports mentioned moving it around in the driveway to let another car out.  Some of the newer engine/fuel systems have serious problems if you start them and then shut them off in too short a period (within a minute or so).  Later when you try to start them they won't start.</p><p>I've had two cars recently with that problem..  a Saturn and a Nissan.  I'd try to start them sometimes after they had been moved around in the driveway and they wouldn't start.  The solution for the Saturn was to hold the gas pedal to the floor and spin the starter for about 20secs and it would reset the ignition system and then it would start.</p></div>
	</div>
</div>
		
